# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: screen-capture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:screen-capture/capturecontroller] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:screen-capture/capturecontroller] A `CaptureController` object is associated with a captured display surface by passing it into a `getDisplayMedia()` call as the value of the options object's `controller` property.
[src:screen-capture/capturecontroller] Creates a new `CaptureController` object instance.
[src:screen-capture/capturecontroller] The captured display surface's current zoom level.
[src:screen-capture/capturecontroller] Decreases the captured display surface's zoom level by one increment.
[src:screen-capture/capturecontroller] Starts forwarding `wheel` events fired on the referenced element to the viewport of an associated captured display surface.
[src:screen-capture/capturecontroller] Returns the different zoom levels supported by the captured display surface.
[src:screen-capture/capturecontroller] Increases the captured display surface's zoom level by one increment.
[src:screen-capture/capturecontroller] Resets the captured display surface's zoom to its initial level, which is `100`.
[src:screen-capture/capturecontroller] Controls whether the captured tab or window will be focused or whether the focus will remain with the tab containing the capturing app.
[src:screen-capture/capturecontroller] Fires when the captured display surface's zoom level changes.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] The **`getDisplayMedia()`** method of the `MediaDevices` interface prompts the user to select and grant permission to capture the contents of a display or portion thereof (such as a window) as a `MediaStream`.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] The resulting stream can then be recorded using the MediaStream Recording API or transmitted as part of a WebRTC session.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] See Using the Screen Capture API for more details and an example.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] An object specifying requirements for the returned `MediaStream`.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] The options for `getDisplayMedia()` work in the same as the constraints for the `MediaDevices.getUserMedia()` method, although in that case only `audio` and `video` can be specified.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] A boolean or a `MediaTrackConstraints` instance; the default value is `true`.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] If this option is omitted or set to `true`, the returned `MediaStream` will contain a video track.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] Since `getDisplayMedia()` requires a video track, if this option is set to `false` the promise will reject with a `TypeError`.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] A boolean or a `MediaTrackConstraints` instance; the default value is `false`.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] A value of `true` indicates that the returned `MediaStream` will contain an audio track, if audio is supported and available for the display surface chosen by the user.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] A `CaptureController` object instance containing methods that can be used to further manipulate the capture session if included.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] An enumerated value specifying whether the browser should offer entire screens in the screen capture options presented to the user alongside tab and window options.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] This option is intended to protect companies from leakage of private information through employee error when using video conferencing apps.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] A boolean; a value of `true` instructs the browser to offer the current tab as the most prominent capture source, that is, as a separate "This Tab" option in the "Choose what to share" options presented to the user.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] This is useful as many app types generally just want to share the current tab.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] For example, a slide deck app might want to let the user stream the current tab containing the presentation to a virtual conference.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] An enumerated value specifying whether the browser should allow the user to select the current tab for capture.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] This helps to avoid the "infinite hall of mirrors" effect experienced when a video conferencing app inadvertently shares its own display.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] An enumerated value specifying whether the browser should display a control to allow the user to dynamically switch the shared tab during screen-sharing.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] This is more convenient than having to go through the whole sharing process again each time a user wants to switch the shared tab.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] An enumerated value specifying whether the browser should include the system audio among the possible audio sources offered to the user.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] An enumerated value that hints to the browser what audio sharing option the user should be presented with alongside window sharing options.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] A `Promise` that resolves to a `MediaStream` containing a video track whose contents come from a user-selected screen area, as well as an optional audio track.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] Thrown if an error or failure does not match any of the other exceptions listed here.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] Thrown if the call to `getDisplayMedia()` was not made from code running due to a transient activation, such as an event handler.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] Or if the browser context is not fully active or does not focused.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] Or if the `controller` options has been already used in creating another `MediaStream`.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] Thrown if the permission to access a screen area was denied by the user, or the current browsing instance is not permitted access to screen sharing (for example by a Permissions Policy).
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] Thrown if no sources of screen video are available for capture.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] Thrown if the user selected a screen, window, tab, or another source of screen data, but a hardware or operating system level error or lockout occurred, preventing the sharing of the selected source.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] Thrown if, after creating the stream, applying any specified constraints fails because no compatible stream could be generated.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] Thrown if the specified `options` include values that are not permitted when calling `getDisplayMedia()`, for example a `video` property set to false, or if any specified `MediaTrackConstraints` are not permitted.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] `min` and `exact` values are not permitted in constraints used in `getDisplayMedia()` calls.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] Because `getDisplayMedia()` could be used in nefarious ways, it can be a source of significant privacy and security concerns.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] For that reason, the specification details measures browsers are required to take in order to fully support `getDisplayMedia()`.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] In the example below a `startCapture()` method is created, which initiates screen capture given a set of options specified by the `displayMediaOptions` parameter.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] This uses `await` to asynchronously wait for `getDisplayMedia()` to resolve with a `MediaStream` which contains the display contents as requested by the specified options.
[src:screen-capture/getdisplaymedia] The stream is then returned to the caller for use, perhaps for adding to a WebRTC call using `RTCPeerConnection.addTrack()` to add the video track from the stream.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Remote desktop applications have varying features.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Some allow attaching to an existing user's session and "remote controlling", either displaying the remote control session or blanking the screen.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Remote access can also be explained as the remote control of a computer by using another device connected via the internet or another network.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] This is widely used by many computer manufacturers and large businesses' help desks for technical troubleshooting of their customers' problems.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Remote desktop software captures the mouse and keyboard inputs from the local computer (client) and sends them to the remote computer (server).
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] The remote computer in turn sends the display commands to the local computer.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] When applications with many graphics including video or 3D models need to be controlled remotely, a remote workstation software that sends the pixels rather than the display commands must be used to provide a smooth, like-local experience.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Remote desktop sharing is accomplished through a common client/server model.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] The client, or VNC viewer, is installed on a local computer and then connects via a network to a server component, which is installed on the remote computer.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] In a typical VNC session, all keystrokes and mouse clicks are registered as if the client were actually performing tasks on the end-user machine.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Remote desktops also have a major advantage for security development, companies are able to permit software engineers who may be dispersed geographically to operate and develop from a computer which can be held within the companies office or cloud environment.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] The target computer in a remote desktop scenario is still able to access all of its core functions.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Many of these core functions, including the main clipboard, can be shared between the target computer and remote desktop client.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Following the onset of COVID-19, the shift to remote-work environments has led many to work from home with devices without enterprise IT support.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] As a result, these workers were reliant on remote desktop software to collaborate and keep their systems available and secure.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] A main use of remote desktop software is remote administration and remote implementation.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] This need arises when software buyers are far away from their software vendor.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Most remote access software can be used for "headless computers": instead of each computer having its own monitor, keyboard, and mouse, or using a KVM switch, one computer can have a monitor, keyboard, mouse, and remote control software, and control many headless computers.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] The duplicate desktop mode is useful for user support and education.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Remote control software combined with telephone communication can be nearly as helpful for novice computer-users as if the support staff were actually there.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Remote desktop software can be used to access a remote computer: a physical personal computer to which a user does not have physical access, but that can be accessed or interacted with.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Unlike servers, remote computers are mainly used for peer to peer connections, where one device is unattended.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] A remote computer connection is generally only possible if both devices have a network connection.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Since the advent of cloud computing remote desktop software can be housed on USB hardware devices, allowing users to connect the device to any PC connected to their network or the Internet and recreate their desktop via a connection to the cloud.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] This model avoids one problem with remote desktop software, which requires the local computer to be switched on at the time when the user wishes to access it remotely.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Remote desktop products are available in three models: hosted service, software, and appliance.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] Tech support scammers use remote desktop software to connect to their victim's computer and will often lock out the computer if the victim does not cooperate.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] A **remote access trojan** (**RAT**, sometimes called **creepware**) is a type of malware that controls a system through a remote network connection.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] While desktop sharing and remote administration have many legal uses, "RAT" connotes criminal or malicious activity.
[src:screen-capture/remote-desktop-software] A RAT is typically installed without the victim's knowledge, often as payload of a Trojan horse, and will try to hide its operation from the victim and from computer security software and other anti-virus software.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] The Screen Capture API introduces additions to the existing Media Capture and Streams API to let the user select a screen or portion of a screen (such as a window) to capture as a media stream.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] This stream can then be recorded or shared with others over the network.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] The Screen Capture API is relatively simple to use.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] Its main method is `MediaDevices.getDisplayMedia()`, whose job is to ask the user to select a screen or portion of a screen to capture in the form of a `MediaStream`.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] The `Promise` returned by `getDisplayMedia()` resolves to a `MediaStream` which streams the captured display surface.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] See the article Using the Screen Capture API for a more in-depth look at how to use the API to capture screen contents as a stream.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] See Using the Element Capture and Region Capture APIs to learn more.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] The **Captured Surface Control API** allows the capturing application to provide limited control over the captured display surface, for example zooming and scrolling its contents.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] See Using the Captured Surface Control API to learn more.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] Represents a single video track; extends the `MediaStreamTrack` class with methods to limit the part of a self-capture stream (for example, a user's screen or window) that is captured.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] Provides methods that can be used to further manipulate a captured display surface (captured via `MediaDevices.getDisplayMedia()`).
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] Provides a static method, `fromElement()`, which returns a `CropTarget` instance that can be used to crop a captured video track to the area in which a specified element is rendered.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] Provides a static method, `fromElement()`, which returns a `RestrictionTarget` instance that can be used to restrict a captured video track to a specified DOM element.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] The `getDisplayMedia()` method is added to the `MediaDevices` interface.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] Similar to `getUserMedia()`, this method creates a promise that resolves with a `MediaStream` containing the display area selected by the user, in a format that matches the specified options.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] The Screen Capture API adds properties to the following dictionaries defined by other specifications.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] A `ConstrainDOMString` indicating what type of display surface is to be captured.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] The value is one of `browser`, `monitor`, or `window`.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] Indicates whether or not the video in the stream represents a logical display surface (that is, one which may not be entirely visible onscreen, or may be completely offscreen).
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] A value of `true` indicates a logical display surface is to be captured.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] Controls whether the audio playing in a tab will continue to be played out of a user's local speakers when the tab is captured, or whether it will be suppressed.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] A value of `true` indicates that it will be suppressed.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] A string which indicates whether or not the display surface currently being captured includes the mouse cursor, and if so, whether it's only visible while the mouse is in motion or if it's always visible.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] The value is one of `always`, `motion`, or `never`.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] A string indicating what type of display surface is currently being captured.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] A boolean value, which is `true` if the video being captured doesn't directly correspond to a single onscreen display area.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] A boolean value, which is `true` if the audio being captured is not played out of the user's local speakers.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] A number representing the ratio of the physical size of a pixel on the captured display surface (displayed at its physical resolution) to the logical size of a CSS pixel on the capturing screen (displayed at its logical resolution).
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] It cannot be used as a constraint or capability.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] A boolean, which is `true` if the current environment supports the `MediaTrackConstraints.displaySurface` constraint.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] A boolean, which is `true` if the current environment supports the constraint `MediaTrackConstraints.logicalSurface`.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] A boolean, which is `true` if the current environment supports the constraint `MediaTrackConstraints.suppressLocalAudioPlayback`.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] A site can also specify a desire to use the Captured Surface Control API via the `captured-surface-control` directive.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] Specifically, the `forwardWheel()`, `increaseZoomLevel()`, `decreaseZoomLevel()`, and `resetZoomLevel()` methods are controlled by this directive.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] The default allowlist for both directives is `self`, which permits any content within the same origin use Screen Capture.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] These methods are considered *powerful features*, which means that even if permission is allowed via a `Permissions-Policy`, the user will still be prompted for permission to use them.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] The Permissions API can be used to query the aggregate permission (from both the website and the user) for using the listed features.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] In addition, the specification requires that a user has recently interacted with the page to use these features — this means that transient activation is required.
[src:screen-capture/screen-capture-api] See the individual method pages for more details.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] A **screenshot** (also known as **screen capture** or **screen grab**) is an analog or digital image that shows the contents of a computer display.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] A screenshot is created by a (film) camera shooting the screen or the operating system or software running on the device powering the display.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] The separate process of taking still frames, images from video or film, is sometimes called still screenshots, screen captures or screen grabs.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] The first screenshots were created with the first interactive computers around 1960.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] Through the 1980s, computer operating systems did not universally have built-in functionality for capturing screenshots.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] Sometimes text-only screens could be dumped to a text file, but the result would only capture the content of the screen, not the appearance, nor were graphics screens preservable this way.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] Some systems had a BSAVE command that could be used to capture the area of memory where screen data was stored, but this required access to a BASIC prompt.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] Systems with composite video output could be connected to a VCR, and entire screencasts preserved this way.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] Most screenshots are raster images, but some vector-based GUI environments like Cairo are capable of generating vector screenshots.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] Screenshot kits were available for standard (film) cameras that included a long antireflective hood to attach between the screen and camera lens, as well as a closeup lens for the camera.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] Polaroid film was popular for capturing screenshots, because of the instant results and close-focusing capability of Polaroid cameras.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] Some web browsers, for example Firefox and Microsoft Edge, have a screenshot tool which can be used to capture a whole web page or part of it.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] The acceptance of screenshots as evidence in legal proceedings varies by jurisdiction and context.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] Court decisions have shown mixed approaches to the evidential value of self-created screenshots.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] Some courts have questioned the reliability of screenshots as standalone evidence due to their potential for manipulation, while others have accepted them as sufficient proof of displayed content when properly authenticated.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] The legal weight given to screenshots often depends on factors such as the chain of custody, technical metadata, and corroborating evidence.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] Screenshots present as RGB data by default.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] These factors require careful attention during the conversion process to ensure optimal print quality.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] Some companies believe the use of screenshots is an infringement of copyright on their program, as it is a derivative work of the widgets and other art created for the software.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] Regardless of copyright, screenshots may still be legally used under the principle of fair use in the U.S. or fair dealing and similar laws in other countries.
[src:screen-capture/screenshot] Screenshots have also been an object of study in academic research, in fields such as law, media studies, and semiotics.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] In this article, we will examine how to use the Screen Capture API and its `getDisplayMedia()` method to capture part or all of a screen for streaming, recording, or sharing during a WebRTC conference session.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] Capturing screen contents as a live `MediaStream` is initiated by calling `navigator.mediaDevices.getDisplayMedia()`, which returns a promise that resolves to a stream containing the live screen contents.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] You can write this code either using an asynchronous function and the `await` operator, as shown above, or using the `Promise` directly, as seen below.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] Either way, the user agent responds by presenting a user interface that prompts the user to choose the screen area to share.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] Both of these implementations of `startCapture()` return the `MediaStream` containing the captured display imagery.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] See Options and constraints, below, for more on both how to specify the type of surface you want as well as other ways to adjust the resulting stream.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] You can then use the captured stream, `captureStream`, for anything that accepts a stream as input.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The examples below show a few ways to make use of the stream.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] For the purposes of the Screen Capture API, a **display surface** is any content object that can be selected by the API for sharing purposes.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] Sharing surfaces include the contents of a browser tab, a complete window, and a monitor (or group of monitors combined together into one surface).
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] A **visible display surface** is a surface which is entirely visible on the screen, such as the frontmost window or tab, or the entire screen.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] A **logical display surface** is one which is in part or completely obscured, either by being overlapped by another object to some extent, or by being entirely hidden or offscreen.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] How these are handled by the Screen Capture API varies.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] Generally, the browser will provide an image which obscures the hidden portion of the logical display surface in some way, such as by blurring or replacing with a color or pattern.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] This is done for security reasons, as the content that cannot be seen by the user may contain data which they do not want to share.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] A user agent might allow the capture of the entire content of an obscured window after gaining permission from the user to do so.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] In this case, the user agent may include the obscured content, either by getting the current contents of the hidden portion of the window or by presenting the most-recently-visible contents if the current contents are not available.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The options object passed into `getDisplayMedia()` is used to set options for the resulting stream.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The `video` and `audio` objects passed into the options object can also hold additional constraints particular to those media tracks.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] See Properties of shared screen tracks for details about additional constraints for configuring a screen-capture stream that are added to `MediaTrackConstraints`, `MediaTrackSupportedConstraints`, and `MediaTrackSettings`).
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] None of the constraints are applied in any way until after the content to capture has been selected.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The constraints alter what you see in the resulting stream.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] For example, if you specify a `width` constraint for the video, it's applied by scaling the video after the user selects the area to share.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] It doesn't establish a restriction on the size of the source itself.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] While display capture is in effect, the machine which is sharing screen contents will display some form of indicator so the user is aware that sharing is taking place.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] `getDisplayMedia()` is most commonly used to capture video of a user's screen (or parts thereof).
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] However, user agents may allow the capture of audio along with the video content.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The source of this audio might be the selected window, the entire computer's audio system, or the user's microphone (or a combination of all of the above).
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] Before starting a project that will require sharing of audio, be sure to check the browser compatibility for `getDisplayMedia()` to see if the browsers you wish compatibility with have support for audio in captured screen streams.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] This allows the user total freedom to select whatever they want, within the limits of what the user agent supports.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] In this example the display surface captured is to be the whole window.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The audio track should ideally have noise suppression and echo cancellation features enabled, as well as an ideal audio sample rate of 44.1kHz, and suppression of local audio playback.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] Capturing audio is always optional, and even when web content requests a stream with both audio and video, the returned `MediaStream` may still have only one video track, with no audio.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The `Promise` returned by `getDisplayMedia()` resolves to a `MediaStream` that contains at least one video stream that contains the screen or screen area, and which is adjusted or filtered based upon the constraints specified when `getDisplayMedia()` was called.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] Privacy and security issues surrounding screen sharing are usually not overly serious, but they do exist.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The largest potential issue is users inadvertently sharing content they did not wish to share.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] For example, privacy and/or security violations can easily occur if the user is sharing their screen and a visible background window happens to contain personal information, or if their password manager is visible in the shared stream.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] This effect can be amplified when capturing logical display surfaces, which may contain content that the user doesn't know about at all, let alone see.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] User agents which take privacy seriously should obfuscate content that is not actually visible onscreen, unless authorization has been given to share that content specifically.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] Before streaming of captured screen contents can begin, the user agent will ask the user to confirm the sharing request, and to select the content to share.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] In this example, the contents of the captured screen area are streamed into a `<video>` element on the same page.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] There isn't all that much code needed in order to make this work, and if you're familiar with using `getUserMedia()` to capture video from a camera, you'll find `getDisplayMedia()` to be very familiar.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] First, some constants are set up to reference the elements on the page to which we'll need access: the `<video>` into which the captured screen contents will be streamed, a box into which logged output will be drawn, and the start and stop buttons that will turn on and off capture of screen imagery.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The object `displayMediaOptions` contains the options to pass into `getDisplayMedia()`; here, the `displaySurface` property is set to `window`, indicating that the whole window should be captured.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] Finally, event listeners are established to detect user clicks on the start and stop buttons.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] This example overrides certain `console` methods to output their messages to the `<pre>` block whose ID is `log`.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] This allows us to use `console.log()` and `console.error()` to log information to the log box in the document.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The `startCapture()` method, below, starts the capture of a `MediaStream` whose contents are taken from a user-selected area of the screen.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] `startCapture()` is called when the "Start Capture" button is clicked.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] After clearing the contents of the log in order to get rid of any leftover text from the previous attempt to connect, `startCapture()` calls `getDisplayMedia()`, passing into it the constraints object defined by `displayMediaOptions`.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] Using `await`, the following line of code does not get executed until after the `Promise` returned by `getDisplayMedia()` resolves.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] Upon resolution, the promise returns a `MediaStream`, which will stream the contents of the screen, window, or other region selected by the user.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The stream is connected to the `<video>` element by storing the returned `MediaStream` into the element's `srcObject`.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The `dumpOptionsInfo()` function—which we will look at in a moment—dumps information about the stream to the log box for educational purposes.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] If any of that fails, the `catch()` clause outputs an error message to the log box.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The `stopCapture()` method is called when the "Stop Capture" button is clicked.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] It stops the stream by getting its track list using `MediaStream.getTracks()`, then calling each track's `stop()` method.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] Once that's done, `srcObject` is set to `null` to make sure it's understood by anyone interested that there's no stream connected.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] For informational purposes, the `startCapture()` method shown above calls a method named `dumpOptions()`, which outputs the current track settings as well as the constraints that were placed upon the stream when it was created.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The track list is obtained by calling `getVideoTracks()` on the captured screen's `MediaStream`.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The HTML starts with an introductory paragraph, then gets into the meat of things.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] A second button, "Stop Capture", which upon being clicked calls `stopCapture()` to terminate capture of screen contents.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] A `<video>` into which the captured screen contents are streamed.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] A `<pre>` block into which logged text is placed by the intercepted `console` method.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The CSS is entirely cosmetic in this example.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] The video is given a border, and its width is set to occupy nearly the entire available horizontal space (`width: 98%`).
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] If your browser supports Screen Capture API, clicking "Start Capture" will present the user agent's interface for selecting a screen, window, or tab to share.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] In order to function when Permissions Policy is enabled, you will need the `display-capture` permission.
[src:screen-capture/using-screen-capture] This can be done using the `Permissions-Policy` HTTP header or—if you're using the Screen Capture API in an `<iframe>`, the `<iframe>` element's `allow` attribute.
